We must use a dynamic structure? We can use a hash table? But Fortran doesn't have built-in hash tables. And we need to remove keys that are >= ai? Then we have to iterate over all keys? That would be O(n) per removal? Then worst-case O(n^2). We can use a balanced BST? Not in Fortran. Alternatively, we can use a stack that we maintain for the entire sequence? The algorithm in the Java code:

        s.clear();
        current = 0;
        for (int ai : a) {
            if (ai <= current) {
                if (k == 1) return false;
                while (!s.isEmpty() && s.lastKey() >= ai) s.pollLastEntry();
                int p = ai - 1;
                while (true) {
                    if (p < 0) return false;
                    int sp = s.getOrDefault(p, 0) + 1;
                    s.put(p, sp);
                    if (sp == k) {
                        s.remove(p);
                        p--;
                    } else {
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
            current = ai;
        }

